main event: A round object, the size of a quarter, was observed in the sky over Twenty-Nine Palms, California on March 17, 1955, for approximately 10 minutes before drifting out of sight.
interesting points: The object was observed for 10 minutes and described as round but with no distinct color.
Observers categorized the sighting as a ground visual observation, and the object was noted to have moved back and forth.
The report suggests the possibility of the object being a balloon and cites regular weather balloon releases in the vicinity as a potential explanation.
The sighting occurred in the vicinity of many weather stations, and the report mentions wind patterns at high altitudes, indicating consideration of atmospheric factors.
Conclusions listed in the report include 'possibly balloon' and 'insufficient data for conclusion', indicating uncertainty about the object's nature.
sighted object: a round object in the sky
